### v6.1 additions - token density + hook audit

#### Token density check

Line count is blind to prose density. A 121-line file can weigh 40K tokens if each line is commit-SHA-dense or paragraph-level. Add this to the audit:

FOR each file in inventory:
  bytes_per_line = bytes / lines
  IF bytes_per_line > 400:
    flag as DENSE
    estimated_tokens = bytes / 4
    IF estimated_tokens > 10000:
      flag as HIGH TOKEN COST regardless of line count

Report DENSE files explicitly in audit output with estimated token cost.

#### Hook audit

Scan the user's hook directories for session-start context leaks:

Paths to check:
- ~/.claude/hooks/
- ~/oxide/hooks/  (if exists)
- Any path declared in `~/.claude/settings.json` under hooks.SessionStart or hooks.UserPromptSubmit

FOR each .sh or .py hook file:
  IF hook fires on SessionStart OR UserPromptSubmit:
    IF it contains `cat ` OR reads a file and outputs its content:
      flag as POTENTIAL CONTEXT LEAK
      show size of files it cats (wc -l each)
      warn if any cat'd file > 50 lines

Report leaky hooks explicitly in audit output. These are invisible to line-count caps because they inject before any file-level rules apply.

#### Why v6.1 exists

Stan's case. He paste-migrated Atlas v6.0 and his /atlas audit reported his system as lean (everything under caps). His actual session init was 30% of context because a session-start-context.sh hook was silently cat-ing a 121-line dense-prose file into every session (40K tokens before the first message). Line count alone missed it. v6.1 catches it.

---

## What /atlas does NOT do

- Does not auto-fix without confirmation
- Does not delete content - moves it (QUEUE to leaf, HANDOFF to LOG, etc.)
- Does not touch `archive/` directories
- Does not read LOG files during audit (not part of session-start payload)
- Does not judge pace, volume, or productivity - neutral state report only
